						               													<description>Where did the great commanders of World War 2 get their start? Fighting in the trenches of World War 1, of course!&amp;#10;Many recall the stalemated trench lines opposing each other for years of futile mass-assaults, but there were daring and heroic action to be found in the small unit trench raids led by rising young officers such as Erwin Rommel. Crossing &amp;quot;No Man&amp;rsquo;s Land,&amp;quot; cutting the barbed wire, and sneaking in under the cover of darkness while a box barrage guarded the raider&amp;rsquo;s flanks, small parties of soldiers would risk all in an effort to keep the enemy off-balance and prepare the way for future actions.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;These quick raids of maneuver and destruction caused panic and pulse-pounding excitement for their brief durations, serving as the stuff of heroic legend for a generation whose nations fought so tragically. Can you lead or defend against a surprise raid among the trenches? Can you keep steady as troops arrive and nerve-wracking bombs go off seemingly from nowhere? Will you triumph among confusion amid the Trenches of Valor?&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Complexity: 2.5 on a 9 scale&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Solitaire Suitability: 6.5 on a 9 scale&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Scale: Each unit is 2 to 10 soldiers, each hex &amp;asymp; 50 meters across, and each turn is about 30 to 60 seconds of real time.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Game Components:&amp;#10;&amp;gt; One 4-page, color Rules booklet&amp;#10;&amp;gt; 42 color, die-cut 3/4&amp;quot; mounted pieces&amp;#10;&amp;gt; One 11&amp;quot; x 17&amp;quot; color game map with tables&amp;#10;&amp;gt; 1 BATTLESSON(TM) sheet&amp;#10;&amp;gt; Part of an introductory wargame series!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
